"about 1250","1259":"1259","1288":"1288","1266":"1266","1453":"1453","1222":"1222","before 1282":"before 1282","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Cowlam, Yorkshire, England":"Cowlam, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Chesham, Buckinghamshire, England":"Chesham, Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hutchinson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): patronymic from the Old French personal name <i>Hucheon</i> (see   Houchin  ) + <i>-son</i>.","Irish: in Ireland and Scotland, adopted for <b>Mac Uisdein</b> and <b>Mac Uistin</b>; see   McCutcheon  .","History: Anne Marbury Hutchinson (1591–1643) and her husband William came from Lincolnshire, England, to MA in 1634. A religious dissident, she led the first attack on the Puritans and was banished from the Massachusetts Bay Colony. She moved to RI in 1638, and, after her husband's death in 1642, settled in NY, where the Hutchinson River was named in her honor. Ironically, the Hutchinson name stayed on in MA and one of her descendants, Thomas Hutchinson (1711–80), was royal governor of Massachusetts Bay Colony."],"variants":[{"name":"Houchin","meanings":["English (Essex): of Norman origin, from the Old French personal name <i>Huchon</i>, a double diminutive of <i>Hue</i> (see   Hugh  ) common in Picardy, corresponding to Old French <i>Hueçon</i>, <i>Huesson</i>, modern French <i>Husson</i>. This was used as a personal name in Scotland, where it also became a surname and was adopted in Gaelic as <i>Huisdean</i> or <i>Uisdean</i>; see   McCutcheon   and compare   Hutch  ."]},{"name":"Hutchison","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Hutchinson  ."]},{"name":"Hutcherson","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Hutchinson  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":65,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":78,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":87,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Hutchinson was born about 1250, in Cowlam, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, James Hutchinson II, was 30 and his mother, Alice Boyville, was 22. He married Edith Wouldbie. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 8 October 1362, in Chesham, Buckinghamshire, England